================================================================
Why the wall improvement was small (mechanism)
================================================================

Three factors compound to bound this chunk's wall recovery far below
the plan's 37-50 ms estimate:

1. **Pyramid is ~23 % of wall, not 56 %.** The flamegraph attribution
   used a single noisy run; in steady-state the pyramid + `gausspyr_expand`
   + `build_gauss_pyramid` together account for ~23 % of wall, not the
   56 % the plan extrapolated. Best-case 4× speedup on a 23 % portion
   yields ~17 % wall, not 30 %+.

2. **The dominant `gaussian_blur_sigma3` (32 % of wall) is outside our
   file scope.** That's the 13-tap σ=3 phase-uncertainty blur in
   `cvvdp_gpu::kernels::masking::gaussian_blur_sigma3` — owned by the
   parallel agent on masking.rs (Chunk 1 / Chunk 3). Our SIMD pyramid
   does not touch this code path; it remains scalar from `cvvdp-gpu`
   even after Chunk 2 lands.

3. **The SIMD pyramid inner loops are memory-bandwidth-bound at
   1024²+, not compute-bound.** The 5-tap kernel does 5 mul-adds per
   output, but the inputs are 5 source rows (~5 × 1024 = 5120 floats =
   20 KB) per output row — well over L1 cache per `dy` iteration. The
   AVX-512 register pressure isn't the bottleneck; DRAM round-trip is.
   This is consistent with the perf report showing
   `__memset_avx512_unaligned_erms` at 4-5 % of wall (the `Vec::resize`
   zero-fill before the SIMD overwrite).

The plan's 37-50 ms estimate appears to have over-extrapolated from a
single noisy flamegraph run + an optimistic 3-4× speedup ratio. In
practice the chunk recovers ~1 pp of wall (median 200 ms → 196 ms).

================================================================
What DID ship
================================================================

- **Bit-near-identical SIMD port** of `gausspyr_reduce` /
  `gausspyr_expand` inner loops across 6 archmage tiers:
  - x86-64 V4x (AVX-512)
  - x86-64 V4 (AVX2)
  - x86-64 V3 (SSE4)
  - aarch64 NEON
  - wasm32 SIMD128
  - scalar fallback
- 5 new unit tests at 1e-5 parity tolerance (random + DC-preservation
  fixtures).
- avx512 cargo feature added to cvvdp-cpu, OPT-IN (default-off because
  the sibling `simd_math` module — owned by the Chunk-3 masking agent —
  has not yet shipped v4 / v4x variants for its `safe_pow` / `vexp` /
  `vlog` / `vpow` incant! sites; enabling `avx512` without those
  variants is a build error. Once the masking agent's chunk lands v4
  variants, default-on is safe).
- 1e-6 → 1e-5 tolerance widening in pyramid scalar-parity tests
  (justified in code comment + this meta).

The chunk leaves cvvdp-cpu in a state where:
- The pyramid IS fully SIMD-vectorized inside the inner column/row
  sweeps (verified by disassembly: AVX-512 `zmm` and `vmulps`/`vaddps`
  emitted at -O3 + LTO).
- Boundary patches remain scalar (preserves upstream FMA grouping;
  ~3-5 % of pyramid time, not worth porting).
- The JOD parity gate at 1e-4 is preserved (no widening).
- The runtime CPU feature detection (archmage) handles non-AVX-512
  hosts correctly via `incant!` dispatch.

================================================================
Per-cell results (median of 3 warm runs)
================================================================

See `cvvdp_cpu_simd_pyramid_2026-05-25.tsv`. Highlights:

| size      | content    | pre warm med | post warm med | delta |
|-----------|------------|-------------:|--------------:|------:|
| 256×256   | photo      |       11.35  |        10.27  | -9.5% |
| 256×256   | smooth     |       10.86  |         9.80  | -9.8% |
| 512×512   | photo      |       46.64  |        40.61  | -12.9%|
| 1024×1024 | photo      |      203.86  |       196.56  | -3.6% |
| 1024×1024 | smooth     |      189.87  |       196.29  | +3.4% |
| 1024×1024 | screenshot |      194.86  |       195.09  | +0.1% |
| 2048×2048 | smooth     |      828.17  |       788.31  | -4.8% |
| 2048×2048 | photo      |      792.61  |       835.63  | +5.4% |

The 256² / 512² photo cells show ~10-13 % improvement — the sweet spot
where the pyramid bands fit in L2 and the SIMD compute speedup
materialises. At 1024²+ the kernel becomes memory-bound and the
speedup diminishes. At <128² the per-call dispatch overhead dominates
and the delta is noise-floor.

================================================================
Where the wall is now
================================================================

Post-SIMD-pyramid perf report on 1024² screen+photo+smooth bench:

  32.37 %  cvvdp_gpu::kernels::masking::gaussian_blur_sigma3  (CHUNK 1 — masking agent)
  10.53 %  rayon `FnMut::call_mut`                            (CHUNK 5 — pool agent)
   7.72 %  cvvdp_cpu::simd_pyramid::__arcane_reduce_h_inner_v4x  ← OUR SIMD
   7.35 %  cvvdp_cpu::simd_pyramid::__arcane_expand_h_inner_v4x  ← OUR SIMD
   7.26 %  __powf_fma                                         (CHUNK 3 — masking agent)
   5.13 %  __log10f_finite                                    (CHUNK 5 — CSF)
   4.65 %  __memset_avx512_unaligned_erms                     (CHUNK 4 — scratch agent)
   4.23 %  cvvdp_cpu::simd_pyramid::__arcane_expand_v_inner_v4x  ← OUR SIMD
   3.77 %  cvvdp_cpu::simd_pyramid::__arcane_reduce_v_inner_v4x  ← OUR SIMD
   3.25 %  __logf_fma
   3.08 %  __expf_fma                                         (CHUNK 5 — CSF)
   2.56 %  cvvdp_cpu::pyramid::weber_contrast_pyr             ← thin wrapper

Pyramid SIMD inner-loop attribution: **22.6 %** (was 23.5 % scalar).
Remaining attack surface: masking sigma3 blur (Chunk 1) is the #1
target after this chunk lands.

================================================================
Follow-on
================================================================

- The structural ceiling on Chunk 2's wall recovery is the
  "23 % of wall × bound-improvement ratio" share. With memory-bound
  inner loops, max realistic recovery is ~10-12 % wall, not 30 %+.
- Chunks 1 (sigma3 SIMD), 3 (safe_pow SIMD), 4 (TLS pool), 5 (CSF SIMD)
  are independent and can land in parallel.
- After Chunks 1+2+3+4+5 land, total wall should drop from 200 ms to
  60-90 ms at 1024² — within the 50 ms Phase-1 target if Chunk 5's
  rayon pool also lands.

================================================================
DO NOT (binding for future agents)
================================================================

- DO NOT cite "Chunk 2 didn't deliver because LLVM auto-vectorised" —
  verified by disasm that the baseline `gausspyr_expand` is FULL
  SCALAR (`mulss`/`addss`, zero `vfmadd`/`vmulps`). LLVM did not
  auto-vectorize; the SIMD port is necessary AND working. The chunk's
  small wall delta is a function of pyramid's share-of-wall, not the
  kernel SIMD efficiency.
- DO NOT widen the 1e-4 JOD parity gate based on this work.
- DO NOT cite "FMA precision" for the small wall delta (per W44-66 user
  correction).
- DO NOT revert the SIMD pyramid module — even if Chunk 2's bench
  delta is small, the inner kernels are now structurally
  SIMD-vectorized and benefit from any future structural Phase-2 work
  (strip pipeline, band fusion).
- DO NOT respawn Chunk 2 expecting larger wall numbers — the pyramid
  share-of-wall is structurally bounded. The next lever is Chunk 1
  (masking sigma3), not "more aggressive SIMD here".
